title: For Sale:  Bushmaster ACR Enhanced Edition with EOTech 512 and Accessories
location: St. John - NW Indiana, Gary, Indiana
postcontent:
Up for sale is my black Bushmaster ACR (Adaptive Combat Rifle) Enhanced Edition. I am selling it because I currently live in Chicago and it just sits in the case at my parent's place in Indiana. I have shot approximately 300-500 rounds through it and it remains in excellent condition. I have been in the military for over 5 years and I have cleaned it and taken care of it just like a standard issue rifle. Along with the rifle, it comes with the original case, sling, MAGPUL pop up sights, and manual. It also comes with 2 PMAGs, MAGPUL MOE foreip, MAGPUL angled foregrip, and the EOTech 512 holographic sight. 
For those of you who aren't familiar with the ACR, it is one of the premier piston operated assault rifles. The last time I checked, the Army is currently testing the ACR, FN SCAR, the HK 416, and a new piston operated version of the Colt M4 for a replacement for the current gas operated carbine. It has also been featured on several FPS video games such as Call of Duty and Battlefield. The spring and action are in the center of the rifle which allows for the collapsible stock, unlike a traditional M4/AR15. It is also considered a "multi-caliber" rifle because the barrel and bolt can easily be changed (in under 2 minutes) to fit 6.8 SPC and eventually 7.62x39 cartridges. Cleaning this rifle is extremely easy as well because all the carbon is captured in the front piston block (no need to clean that pesky star chamber). The ACR is a rifle for someone who is looking for the next generation assault rifle. It has less recoil, more adaptability, more versatility, and better performance than the 60yr old M16/M4 platform and it is completely ambidextrous out of the box. This rifle truly is the best rifle I have ever had the chance to shoot.

Interested buyers please email me and we can discuss shipping details. I am not opposed to meeting up to discuss the sale.

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson -- Smith &Wesson .38 Caliber Safety Hammerless
postcontent: 38 Safety Hammerless, 4th Model, DA aka Lemon Squeezer” Smith &Wesson .38 Caliber Safety, 4th Model, Double Action “Lemon Squeezer” with mother-of-pearl grips and extensive engraving including the name “Buck Garrett” on the left side and the initials “BG” on the left grip. Produced from 1898 – 1907. This model was unusual in in that the hammer was concealed, so it could only be fired as a double action, and a safety bar set into the backstrap had to be simultaneously squeezed with the trigger to fire (led to the nickname “Lemon Squeezer”). This gun was manufactured in 1899, and requires a copy of a FFL or C&R for shipment. It is in overall excellent condition, both cosmetically and mechanically. It was not factory engraved, but the engraving is very high quality. Likewise, the pearl grips were not on the gun when it was shipped from the factory. But they are of high quality and fit well. The gun is inscribed “Buck Garrett” on the left side, and has the initials, “BG” on the left grip. Buck Garrett’s law officer career started at the age of 18 as a “posse man” in the Indian Territory. From this early start, he graduated to being a deputy sheriff, and then was a federal marshal for nearly 20 years. During this time, he worked with fellow officers in rounding up the celebrated Dalton gang, the Nations gang, the Johns gang, the Oates gang and dozens of other outlaw gangs whose names brought fear to settlers and trainmen. After he retired as a marshal, he ran for sheriff in Ardmore, OK and was elected several times. Sheriff Buck, like many law officers of that time, frequently kept confiscated weapons and had the better ones fixed up specifically for his collections. He was reputed to be the possessor of over 100 pistols. Pistols of all calibers and conditions from tiny .25s to giant .45s. They were ivory handled, pearl handled, wooden handled, horn handled, and were blued, chromed, or silver plated and some were extensively engraved.

title: For Sale:  Kel-Tec PF9, +Belt Clip, Fluffed and Buffed, BETTER than new
postcontent:
Kel-Tec PF9 with less than 120 rounds through it. 
Brown frame, blued slide. Has belt clip installed (in matching blued finish). 
Gun has been "fluffed and buffed" and operates MUCH better than new. 
Gun looks and feels new, but has many improvements over new. 
Looking for $300.

Comes with 1 magazine, finger extension mag bottom (installed), flat mag bottom, trigger lock, manual, original hard case, belt clip (installed), original frame pins (if want to remove belt clip).  
Basically everything you get with the new gun, plus the belt clip. 

Also, I filed down the sharp edges on the ridges that are on the back of the grip.
This greatly improved comfort for me when shooting without gloves.  Visually no different, simply more comfortable. 

Whats a "fluff and buff"?
You can google it, but basically it is doing all the hand finish work that Kel-Tec does not do to keep prices down.  This helps the gun operate smoother, giving better feel and (IMO) better accuracy and less perceived recoil. 
Here is what was done:
Polished feed ramp
Smoothed out machining and casting marks in areas of contact on slide and frame
Broke sharp edge at bottom of bore in frame where barrel rides and polished inside bore
Broke sharp edges where feed ramp meets frame
Polished slide rails
Polished outside of chamber where it slides against slide
Broke sharp edges of magazine where grips casing and polished these edges
**NOTE:  Polished means improved surface finish through polishing using a felt bob and various stages of polishing compound. I only went up to a high-gloss in the feed areas and around the chamber, as these areas build up carbon quickly and the higher gloss finish does a better job of resisting build-up.

title: For Sale:  Sig Sauer P225 (aka German P6) + extra mag
postcontent:
Classic single-stack Sig, civilian version of pistol used by police in Germany for years. Original matching barrel, rifling good, Sig Sauer reliability.  

I don't have too much information on its origin other than that it appears to have been manufactured in the late 80s (based on serial number search), and that it's had some custom work done to it, such as:

- replaced guide rod
- lightened trigger pull
- polished muzzle (god knows why)
- the letter 'T' inscribed on the top of the barrel, which I was told is the mark of a popular gunsmith

Given the slimmer profile of this gun, it is very comfortable to hold and possibly even carry. Love the classic checkered grips, love how easy it is to shoot accurately.

Only downside I can see here is wear on frame and finishing slide do it's age. I think this is kinda cool though since it adds a bit of character to the gun.

These pistols are a bit difficult to come by as they are no longer manufactured, so my price reflects that. Comes with extra factory mag, which are pricey.

Face to face. No trades. Cash only. Will require TX ID and fill out bill of sale.
